2–Deceased","1513–1565":"1513–1565","1465–1565":"1465–1565","1470–1560":"1470–1560","1513":"1513","1579":"1579","1512":"1512","1566":"1566","1565":"1565","1465":"1465","1541":"1541","about 1513":"about 1513","1560":"1560","1470":"1470","1519":"1519","1490":"1490","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Great Gransden, Huntingdonshire, England, Kingdom of England":"Great Gransden, Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom","Great Gransden, Huntingdonshire, England":"Great Gransden, Huntingdonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Seeley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname for a person with a cheerful disposition, from Middle English <i>seli</i> ‘happy, fortunate’ (Old English <i>sǣlig</i>, from <i>sǣl</i> ‘happiness, good fortune’). The word was also occasionally used as a female personal name during the Middle Ages. The sense ‘pitiable’, which developed into modern English <i>silly</i>, is not attested before the 15th century. See also   Selman  .","Altered form of German   Seele  , respelled to preserve the bisyllabic pronunciation of the German name."],"variants":[{"name":"Seely","meanings":["English (East Anglia): variant of   Seeley  ."]},{"name":"Selley","meanings":["English (Devon):","variant of   Seeley  .","habitational name from Selly Oak in Northfield (Worcestershire), probably from Old English <i>scelf</i> ‘shelf, ledge’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’."]},{"name":"Selman","meanings":["English: nickname for a happy or fortunate man, from Middle English <i>seli</i> ‘happy, fortunate’ (Old English <i>sǣlig</i>) + <i>man</i>. The nickname was also used as a personal name. See also   Seeley  .","English: from the Middle English nickname or female personal name <i>Sely</i> (see   Seeley  ) + <i>-man</i>, hence an occupational name for a servant of someone so called.","Americanized form of German <b>Sellmann</b> (see   Sellman  )."]},{"name":"Seelye","meanings":["English: variant of   Seeley  ."]},{"name":"Sealy","meanings":["English: variant of   Seeley  .","Welsh: from the male personal name <i>Selyf</i> or <i>Seleu</i>, medieval Welsh vernacular forms of   Solomon   which were replaced by that form in the Welsh Bible of 1588.","Irish: variant of   Shelley   (in counties Cork and Kerry); elsewhere of English or Welsh origin, as in 1 above and 2."]},{"name":"Sealey","meanings":["English: variant of   Seeley  ."]},{"name":"Seley","meanings":["English: variant of   Seeley  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Seeley was born in 1490, in Great Gransden, Huntingdonshire, England, his father, William Seeley, was 26 and his mother, Elizabeth, was 20. He married Dorothy in 1512. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1513, in Great Gransden, Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 23."},"et":{"1490–1513":"1490–1513","1490–1565":"1490–1565","1519–1579":"1519–1579","1541–1566":"1541–1566","1512–Male":"1512–Surnud","1513–1565":"1513–1565","1465–1565":"1465–1565","1470–1560":"1470–1560","1513":"1513","1579":"1579","1512":"1512","1566":"1566","1565":"1565","1465":"1465","1541":"1541","about 1513":"umbes 1513","1560":"1560","1470":"1470","1519":"1519","1490":"1490","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Great Gransden, Huntingdonshire, England, Kingdom of England":"Great Gransden, Huntingdonshire, Inglismaa,